
1. How does Flask receive form data from HTML?

Flask uses request.form to access HTML form data. Import request from Flask and check request.method == 'POST'.

python
from flask import Flask, request, render_template

@app.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])
def login():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        username = request.form['username']
        password = request.form['password']
        return f'Logged in: {username}'
    return render_template('login.html')

HTML form:

xml
<form method="POST">
    <input type="text" name="username">
    <input type="password" name="password">
    <button type="submit">Login</button>
</form>



2. What is the purpose of using POST in form submission?

	POST sends data securely (not visible in URL) and handles sensitive info like passwords, unlike GET which shows data in URL.

| POST                 | GET                       |
| -------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Data in request body | Data in URL (?name=rahul) |
| Secure (passwords)   | Bookmarks, search         |
| No length limit      | 255 char limit            |
| Form submissions     | Page parameters           |

<form method="POST">  # Login forms
<form method="GET">   # Search forms



3. How do you compare login details in Flask?

	Check form data against stored credentials:

python
@app.route('/login', methods=['POST'])
def login():
    username = request.form['username']
    password = request.form['password']
    
    if username == 'admin' and password == 'secret123':
        return 'Login Successful!'
    else:
        return 'Invalid credentials'

Better (secure):

python
users = {'admin': 'hashed_password_here'}
if username in users and check_password(password, users[username]):
    return 'Welcome!'



4. How do you send error messages back to templates?

Pass error message as variable to template:

python
@app.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])
def login():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        if request.form['username'] != 'admin':
            return render_template('login.html', error="Invalid username!")
    
    return render_template('login.html')

HTML displays error:

xml
{% if error %}
    <div class="alert alert-danger">{{ error }}</div>
{% endif %}
<form method="POST">...</form>



5. Why is a templates folder important for login pages?

	Flask automatically looks for HTML files in templates/ folder. Login pages need dynamic content (error messages, user data) that only templates can handle.

templates/
└── login.html     # Dynamic login form
static/
└── style.css      # Static styling

Without templates folder:

❌ FileNotFoundError: login.html not found
❌ Can't pass variables to plain HTML

Login workflow:

Flask → templates/login.html → User fills form → POST → Check → Redirect or error

Forms + Templates = Complete login system! 🔐✨


